{{Infobox organization | logo = | type = Transparency project | key_people = | footnotes = | name = Airwars | founded_date = {{start date and age|df=yes|2014||}} | founder = Chris Woods | headquarters = London, England <!-- this parameter modifies "Headquarters" --> | origins = | area_served = Iraq, Syria and Libya | product = | focus = | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsid = | owner = | Non-profit_slogan = | homepage = [https://airwars.org/ Airwars] | dissolved = }}
'''Airwars''' is a London, UK-based<ref>{{cite web | last=Press | first=Associated | title=Pentagon: 801 civilians killed in coalition airstrikes | website=Fox News | date=November 30, 2017 | url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/11/30/pentagon-801-civilians-killed-in-coalition-airstrikes.html | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> not-for-profit company that tracks and archives the international air war against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] and other groups in [[Iraq]], [[Syria]] and [[Libya]], and assesses and follows up on credible allegations of civilian casualties from [[Combined Joint Task Force – Operation Inherent Resolve|coalition]] and Russian airstrikes.<ref>{{cite web | last=Press | first=Associated | title=Rights groups: Many casualties in Mosul from heavy weapons | website=Fox News | date=June 9, 2017 | url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/06/09/rights-groups-many-casualties-in-mosul-from-heavy-weapons.html | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Battle against ISIS in Mosul left over 9,000 dead | website=New York Post | date=December 20, 2017 | url=https://nypost.com/2017/12/20/battle-against-isis-in-mosul-left-over-9000-dead/ | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Reuters News - U.S.-led forces acknowledge killing 51 more civilians in Iraq, Syria | website=Townhall | date=October 26, 2017 | url=https://townhall.com/news/world/2017/10/26/usled-forces-acknowledge-killing-51-more-civilians-in-iraq-syria-n2400769 | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>
Airwars was founded by investigative journalist Chris Woods<ref>{{cite web | title=Syria becomes a testing ground as Russia revives its defence industry | website=The National | url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/syria-becomes-a-testing-ground-as-russia-revives-its-defence-industry-1.712786 | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> in the fall of 2014. It was registered in England and Wales as a private company limited by guarantee in August 2016.<ref name="ch">{{cite web|title=AIRWARS - Overview|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/10314448|publisher=[[Companies House]]|accessdate=8 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>
==Methodology==
Airwars draws on a number of information sources including [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]], monitoring groups such as the [[United Nations Assistance Mission in Iraq]] (UNAMI), international and local news agencies, social media sites including local residents’ groups, in-country researchers, [[Facebook]] pages, [[YouTube]] footage of incidents, [[twitter|tweets]] relating to specific events and from military and other government sources.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our methodology|url=https://airwars.org/methodology/|website=Airwars|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>
==Funding==
Sources of funding include [[Joseph Rowntree Charitable Trust]], [[Open Society Foundations]] and [[:nl:Stichting Democratie en Media|Stichting Democratie en Media]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Non profit. What is Airwars ? | website=www.sneezz.info | date=January 20, 2017 | url=http://www.sneezz.info/2017/01/non-profit-what-airwars | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>
